// Auto-migrated from the original static guide HTML. Structural markup
// and code samples are preserved; inline styles, scripts, and the guide's
// own bespoke syntax-highlight token classes were stripped so every guide
// renders through the one shared GuideReader stylesheet.
export const html: string = "<section id=\"section\">\n<div>\n<span>INDEX OF SHEETS</span>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"#foundations\"><span>01</span> What Is Authentication?</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#contrib-auth\"><span>02</span> django.contrib.auth</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#passwords\"><span>03</span> Password Hashing</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#login-logout\"><span>04</span> Login &amp; Logout</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#custom-user\"><span>05</span> The Custom User Model</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#permissions\"><span>06</span> Permissions &amp; Groups</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#protecting-views\"><span>07</span> Protecting Views</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#auth-forms\"><span>08</span> Auth Forms</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#password-reset\"><span>09</span> Password Reset Flow</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#signals\"><span>10</span> Signals &amp; Signup Hooks</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#sessions\"><span>11</span> Sessions, Deeply</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#hardening\"><span>12</span> Production Hardening</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#auth-flow\"><span>13</span> The Full Auth Request</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#auth-tips\"><span>14</span> Pro Tips &amp; Pitfalls</a></li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"foundations\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 01 / FOUNDATIONS</span>\n<h2>What is \"authentication,\" actually?</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Before opening a single Django file, you need to understand the problem auth solves at the protocol level \u2014 because HTTP itself has no concept of \"being logged in\" at all.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Absolute Scratch</h4><span>THE CORE PROBLEM</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>HTTP is <strong>stateless</strong>. Every request a browser sends is a self-contained, amnesiac event \u2014 the server that handles request #2 has no memory of request #1, even if both came from the same browser, half a second apart. There is no built-in concept of \"this is the same visitor as before.\"</p>\n<p>So how does a site recognize you across multiple requests \u2014 letting you load a page, then click a link, and still be \"logged in\"? The answer is a trick almost the entire web relies on: <strong>the server gives the browser a small token (a cookie) the first time it proves its identity, and the browser dutifully attaches that same token to every subsequent request.</strong> The server then just has to recognize the token, not re-verify a password every time.</p>\n<p>Authentication, at its core, is just this: <strong>verify identity once (a password check), then issue a token that stands in for that identity for a while.</strong> Everything else \u2014 login forms, password hashing, permissions \u2014 is built on top of that one idea.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Authentication vs. Authorization \u2014 a distinction worth nailing down early</h3>\n<div class=\"grid2\">\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">AUTHENTICATION</span>\n<p><strong>\"Who are you?\"</strong> The process of verifying identity \u2014 typically a username/password check. The outcome is a known, trusted identity attached to the request: <code>request.user</code>.</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">AUTHORIZATION</span>\n<p><strong>\"What are you allowed to do?\"</strong> Once identity is known, authorization decides whether <em>this specific</em> known user can view this page, edit this row, or access this feature. Permissions and groups (Sheet 06) live here.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>NAMING TRAP</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>People say \"auth\" to mean both, constantly, and it causes real bugs: a view that only checks <em>\"is someone logged in?\"</em> (authentication) when it actually needed to check <em>\"is this logged-in person allowed to edit THIS post?\"</em> (authorization) is a textbook access-control vulnerability. Keep the two words mentally separate even when colleagues don't.</p></div>\n</div>\n<h3>Sessions vs. tokens \u2014 the two dominant strategies</h3>\n<p>Django's default toolkit uses <strong>session-based authentication</strong>: the cookie holds only a random session ID; the actual \"who is this and what do they have access to\" data lives server-side, in a session store. This is different from <strong>token-based authentication</strong> (e.g. JWTs, common in pure APIs), where the token itself carries the identity data, cryptographically signed, and the server verifies it without a database lookup.</p>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th></th><th>Session-based (Django default)</th><th>Token-based (e.g. JWT)</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td>Where identity lives</td><td>Server-side store; cookie holds only an ID</td><td>Inside the token itself, signed</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Revocation</td><td>Instant \u2014 delete the server-side session</td><td>Hard \u2014 a signed token is valid until it expires, unless you maintain a blocklist</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Best for</td><td>Traditional server-rendered sites (what this guide covers)</td><td>Stateless APIs, mobile/SPA backends, microservices</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"pillquote\">\"A session is not magic \u2014 it's a database row and a cookie, pointing at each other.\"</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"contrib-auth\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 02 / WHAT SHIPS IN THE BOX</span>\n<h2>django.contrib.auth \u2014 the batteries that are already included</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">In vanilla development, \"auth\" usually means writing a <code>users</code> table, a login route, password hashing code, and session-handling middleware \u2014 by hand, from zero, on every single project. Django ships an entire pre-built app, <code>django.contrib.auth</code>, that does all of it, and it's already listed in <code>INSTALLED_APPS</code> on a fresh project.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>WHAT'S ACTUALLY INSIDE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Four pieces arrive together, and understanding what each one is responsible for prevents a lot of later confusion:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>A <code>User</code> model</strong> \u2014 a database table for accounts (username, email, password hash, flags like <code>is_active</code>).</li>\n<li><strong>Authentication backends</strong> \u2014 pluggable logic that knows <em>how</em> to verify credentials (the default checks username + password against the hash).</li>\n<li><strong>Middleware</strong> \u2014 <code>AuthenticationMiddleware</code>, which runs on every request and attaches <code>request.user</code> automatically, based on the session.</li>\n<li><strong>Views &amp; forms</strong> \u2014 ready-made login, logout, and password-management screens you can use immediately or override.</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3><code>request.user</code> \u2014 the most important object in this entire guide</h3>\n<p>Because <code>AuthenticationMiddleware</code> runs on every request, every view you write automatically receives a populated <code>request.user</code> \u2014 no extra code needed. This single attribute is the foundation everything else in this guide builds on.</p>\n<pre><code><span>def</span> <span>dashboard</span>(request):\n <span>if</span> request.user.is_authenticated:\n <span>return</span> render(request, <span>\"dashboard.html\"</span>, {<span>\"user\"</span>: request.user})\n <span>return</span> redirect(<span>\"login\"</span>)</code></pre>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>request.user IS NEVER None</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A common vanilla-dev instinct is to check <code>if request.user:</code>. Don't \u2014 <strong>Django always sets <code>request.user</code> to something</strong>, even for visitors who never logged in. If nobody's logged in, it's set to an instance of <code>AnonymousUser</code>, a stand-in object that responds to the same interface (<code>.is_authenticated</code> returns <code>False</code>, <code>.is_staff</code> returns <code>False</code>) so your templates and views never crash from a missing attribute. Always check <code>request.user.is_authenticated</code>, never truthiness.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>The default <code>User</code> model's fields</h3>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Purpose</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>username</code></td><td>Unique login identifier (default backend)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>password</code></td><td>Never plaintext \u2014 a hashed, salted string (Sheet 03)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>email</code></td><td>Not unique or required by default \u2014 a frequent source of surprise</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>is_active</code></td><td>Soft \"account disabled\" switch \u2014 inactive users can't log in at all</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>is_staff</code></td><td>Can log into the <code>/admin/</code> site</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>is_superuser</code></td><td>Bypasses all permission checks entirely</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>last_login</code></td><td>Auto-updated timestamp</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>is_staff vs is_superuser vs is_active</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>These three flags are independent and frequently confused. A user can be <code>is_staff=True</code> (can enter the admin) without being <code>is_superuser=True</code> (which grants every permission unconditionally). And <code>is_active=False</code> overrides everything \u2014 an inactive superuser still can't log in anywhere. Think of <code>is_active</code> as the master breaker switch.</p></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"passwords\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 03 / TRUST FOUNDATIONS</span>\n<h2>Password hashing \u2014 from absolute zero</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">This is the single most consequence-laden topic in this whole guide. Get it wrong in a vanilla project and a database breach turns into every user's password being exposed in plaintext, everywhere they reused it. Django gets it right automatically \u2014 but understanding <em>why</em> is non-negotiable.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Absolute Scratch</h4><span>WHY NOT JUST STORE THE PASSWORD?</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>The naive approach: store <code>password = \"hunter2\"</code> in the database, and compare it on login. The catastrophic flaw: <strong>anyone who ever gets read access to that database table \u2014 a hacker, a careless backup, a malicious insider \u2014 instantly has every user's real password</strong>, in cleartext, ready to try on their email, their bank, every other site they reused that password on.</p>\n<p>The fix is a <strong>one-way hash function</strong>: a mathematical function that turns \"hunter2\" into something like <code>5f4dcc3b5aa765d6...</code> \u2014 and critically, there is no inverse function to turn the hash back into the password. To check a login attempt, Django doesn't decrypt anything; it hashes the <em>submitted</em> password the same way and compares the two hashes. The real password is never stored, anywhere, ever.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<figure class=\"diagram\">\n<svg aria-label=\"Diagram showing a password going through a one-way hash function with a salt to produce a hash that is stored, with the original password never recoverable\" role=\"img\" viewbox=\"0 0 640 180\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"320\" y=\"18\">ONE-WAY HASHING \u2014 NO PATH BACK</text>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\" width=\"140\" x=\"20\" y=\"40\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"90\" y=\"66\">\"hunter2\"</text>\n<path d=\"M160,62 L228,62\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#2f6b46\" height=\"64\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\" width=\"170\" x=\"230\" y=\"30\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"10\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"315\" y=\"55\">PBKDF2 / Argon2</text>\n<text fill=\"#D9E7DD\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"8.5\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"315\" y=\"70\">+ random salt</text>\n<text fill=\"#D9E7DD\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"8.5\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"315\" y=\"84\">+ many iterations</text>\n<path d=\"M400,62 L468,62\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\" width=\"150\" x=\"470\" y=\"40\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"9.5\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"545\" y=\"60\">pbkdf2_sha256$...</text>\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"8\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"545\" y=\"74\">stored in DB</text>\n<path d=\"M545,90 Q 545,140 90,140 Q 50,140 50,88\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#a3432e\" stroke-dasharray=\"4 3\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<text fill=\"#a3432e\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"320\" y=\"155\"> no function exists to reverse this arrow</text>\n</svg>\n<figcaption>Hashing is deliberately one-directional \u2014 verification re-hashes the attempt and compares, it never decrypts.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<h3>Salting \u2014 defeating precomputed lookup tables</h3>\n<p>If everyone's \"password123\" hashed to the exact same string, an attacker could precompute a giant table of common-password\u2192hash pairs once (a \"rainbow table\") and instantly reverse-lookup any leaked hash. A <strong>salt</strong> \u2014 a random string mixed in before hashing, unique <em>per user</em> \u2014 defeats this: even two users with the identical password get completely different stored hashes, because each gets its own salt. Django generates and stores the salt automatically, bundled right inside the hash string itself.</p>\n<pre><code><span># what's actually stored in the database \u2014 one string, three parts</span>\npbkdf2_sha256$<span>600000</span>$<span>kj3HnP9...</span>$<span>xY7qZp2...</span>\n<span># ^algorithm ^iterations ^salt ^the actual hash</span></code></pre>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Mental Model</h4><span>ANALOGY</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Think of hashing like putting a document through a paper shredder, photographing the resulting confetti pile, and throwing the original document away. You can never reconstruct the document from the photo \u2014 but if someone hands you a <em>new</em> document, you can shred it the exact same way and compare confetti photos to check if it's the same document. The salt is like shredding each document with a uniquely shaped shredder, so identical documents never produce identical-looking confetti.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Why iterations matter \u2014 slowing the attacker down on purpose</h3>\n<p>Modern hashing algorithms deliberately make each hash computation <em>slow</em> \u2014 thousands of internal iterations \u2014 so that an attacker who steals a database of hashes and tries to brute-force guesses can only attempt a few thousand passwords per second per machine, instead of billions. Django's default, PBKDF2, runs hundreds of thousands of iterations and Django increases this number across releases as hardware gets faster.</p>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Hasher</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>PBKDF2PasswordHasher</code></td><td>Default. Solid, FIPS-friendly, the safe default choice.</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>Argon2PasswordHasher</code></td><td>Winner of the Password Hashing Competition; stronger against GPU/ASIC cracking. Requires <code>pip install argon2-cffi</code>. <span class=\"security-grade\">RECOMMENDED FOR NEW PROJECTS</span></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>BCryptSHA256PasswordHasher</code></td><td>Widely battle-tested, common outside the Django world too.</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<pre><code><span># settings.py \u2014 put your preferred hasher FIRST; Django still verifies old hashes</span>\n<span># using whichever algorithm matches what's actually stored, then re-hashes on next login</span>\nPASSWORD_HASHERS = [\n <span>\"django.contrib.auth.hashers.Argon2PasswordHasher\"</span>,\n <span>\"django.contrib.auth.hashers.PBKDF2PasswordHasher\"</span>,\n]</code></pre>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Critical Gotcha</h4><span>NEVER WRITE YOUR OWN HASHING CODE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>Never use <code>hashlib.md5()</code>, <code>hashlib.sha256()</code> alone, or any hand-rolled scheme for passwords. Generic hash functions are built to be <em>fast</em> (good for file checksums, terrible for passwords \u2014 fast means an attacker can try billions of guesses per second). Always go through <code>django.contrib.auth.hashers.make_password()</code> / <code>check_password()</code>, or simply <code>user.set_password()</code>, and let Django's dedicated, slow, salted password hashers do the work.</p></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"login-logout\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 04 / THE HANDSHAKE</span>\n<h2>Login &amp; Logout \u2014 turning a password into a session</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Three Django functions do almost all of the real work here: <code>authenticate()</code>, <code>login()</code>, and <code>logout()</code>. They're deliberately separate steps, and understanding why they're split apart clarifies a lot of \"why do I need both of these?\" confusion.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>TWO SEPARATE STEPS, ON PURPOSE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p><code>authenticate(request, username=..., password=...)</code> only <em>checks</em> credentials \u2014 it runs them through the configured authentication backend(s), and returns either a real <code>User</code> object (success) or <code>None</code> (failure). <strong>It does not log anyone in.</strong> It's a pure verification step, with no side effects.</p>\n<p><code>login(request, user)</code> is the step that actually creates the session \u2014 it writes the user's ID into the session store and sets the session cookie on the response. Splitting these apart means you can verify credentials for reasons that <em>aren't</em> \"log this person in\" (an API check, a re-auth prompt before a sensitive action) without accidentally starting a session.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib.auth <span>import</span> authenticate, login, logout\n<span>from</span> django.shortcuts <span>import</span> render, redirect\n\n<span>def</span> <span>login_view</span>(request):\n <span>if</span> request.method == <span>\"POST\"</span>:\n username = request.POST[<span>\"username\"</span>]\n password = request.POST[<span>\"password\"</span>]\n user = authenticate(request, username=username, password=password)\n <span>if</span> user <span>is not</span> <span>None</span>:\n login(request, user) <span># NOW the session is created</span>\n <span>return</span> redirect(<span>\"dashboard\"</span>)\n <span>else</span>:\n <span>return</span> render(request, <span>\"login.html\"</span>, {<span>\"error\"</span>: <span>\"Invalid credentials\"</span>})\n <span>return</span> render(request, <span>\"login.html\"</span>)\n\n<span>def</span> <span>logout_view</span>(request):\n logout(request) <span># wipes the session entirely</span>\n <span>return</span> redirect(<span>\"home\"</span>)</code></pre>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>VAGUE ERROR MESSAGES, ON PURPOSE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>Notice the error message above says \"Invalid credentials,\" not \"wrong password\" or \"no such username.\" Telling an attacker <em>which</em> part was wrong lets them enumerate which usernames/emails actually exist in your system \u2014 a real information leak. Always return the same generic message regardless of whether the username or the password was the actual problem.</p></div>\n</div>\n<h3>Don't reinvent this \u2014 use the built-in views</h3>\n<p>Writing the view above is a useful learning exercise, but production code almost always reaches for Django's already-built, already-tested views instead, wired in via <code>urls.py</code>:</p>\n<pre><code><span># urls.py</span>\n<span>from</span> django.contrib.auth <span>import</span> views <span>as</span> auth_views\n\nurlpatterns = [\n path(<span>\"login/\"</span>, auth_views.LoginView.as_view(template_name=<span>\"login.html\"</span>), name=<span>\"login\"</span>),\n path(<span>\"logout/\"</span>, auth_views.LogoutView.as_view(), name=<span>\"logout\"</span>),\n]</code></pre>\n<p>These built-in views already handle CSRF protection, the POST/redirect/GET pattern, \"next page\" redirect handling via a <code>?next=</code> query parameter, and rate-limit-friendly error handling \u2014 all the fiddly correctness details a hand-rolled view tends to miss on a first pass.</p>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>WHERE DOES LOGIN REDIRECT TO?</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<pre><code><span># settings.py</span>\nLOGIN_URL = <span>\"/login/\"</span> <span># where @login_required sends anonymous users</span>\nLOGIN_REDIRECT_URL = <span>\"/dashboard/\"</span> <span># where LoginView sends users after success</span>\nLOGOUT_REDIRECT_URL = <span>\"/\"</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"custom-user\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 05 / THE DAY-ONE DECISION</span>\n<h2>The custom User model \u2014 the choice you can't easily undo later</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">This is the single most important decision in this entire guide, because of one brutal fact: <strong>swapping your User model after you've already run migrations and have real data is extremely painful</strong> \u2014 it touches every <code>ForeignKey</code> to <code>User</code> across your whole codebase. Django's own documentation is blunt about this, and the official advice is equally blunt:</p>\n<div class=\"pillquote\">\"If you're starting a new project, it's highly recommended to set up a custom user model, even if the default User model is sufficient for you.\"</div>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>WHY THE DEFAULT ISN'T ENOUGH</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>The built-in <code>User</code> model is intentionally generic \u2014 it has to work for every Django project on Earth, so it makes conservative, sometimes inconvenient choices: email isn't unique or required, there's no room for a phone number or a profile picture without bolting on a separate model, and you can't rename <code>username</code> to <code>email</code> as the login field after the fact. A <strong>custom user model</strong> just means: define your own <code>User</code> class, point Django at it from day one, and you fully control its shape forever after.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Two approaches, depending on how much you want to change</h3>\n<div class=\"grid2\">\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">EXTEND AbstractUser</span>\n<p>Keeps everything the default <code>User</code> has (username, password, flags) and lets you <em>add</em> fields. The easy, common path.</p>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib.auth.models <span>import</span> AbstractUser\n\n<span>class</span> <span>User</span>(AbstractUser):\n bio = models.TextField(blank=<span>True</span>)\n avatar = models.ImageField(upload_to=<span>\"avatars/\"</span>, blank=<span>True</span>)</code></pre>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">EXTEND AbstractBaseUser</span>\n<p>Gives you a nearly blank slate \u2014 you define every field, including how login works (e.g. email instead of username). More control, more responsibility.</p>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib.auth.models <span>import</span> AbstractBaseUser\n\n<span>class</span> <span>User</span>(AbstractBaseUser):\n email = models.EmailField(unique=<span>True</span>)\n USERNAME_FIELD = <span>\"email\"</span> <span># login is by email now</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Wiring it up \u2014 the one setting that ties it all together</h3>\n<pre><code><span># settings.py</span>\nAUTH_USER_MODEL = <span>\"accounts.User\"</span> <span># \"appname.ModelName\"</span></code></pre>\n<p>Every place in your code that needs to refer to \"the user model\" generically \u2014 rather than importing your concrete class \u2014 should use Django's helper, so your code keeps working even if the custom model later moves or changes name:</p>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib.auth <span>import</span> get_user_model\nUser = get_user_model()\n\n<span># and in models.py, for ForeignKeys specifically, use the settings reference directly:</span>\n<span>from</span> django.conf <span>import</span> settings\nauthor = models.ForeignKey(settings.AUTH_USER_MODEL, on_delete=models.CASCADE)</code></pre>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Critical Gotcha</h4><span>THIS MUST HAPPEN BEFORE YOUR FIRST MIGRATION</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p><code>AUTH_USER_MODEL</code> can only be set <strong>before</strong> you run <code>migrate</code> for the first time on a project. Once Django has built the database schema around the default <code>auth.User</code>, switching it requires a genuinely painful manual migration involving every related table. The practical rule, with no real exceptions: <strong>every new Django project should define a (possibly minimal) custom user model in its very first commit</strong>, even if it changes nothing about the default behavior on day one \u2014 it's nearly free insurance against a much harder migration in month six.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>PUT IT IN ITS OWN APP</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>Convention favors a small, dedicated app \u2014 commonly named <code>accounts</code> or <code>users</code> \u2014 that holds only the custom user model and directly related logic. This keeps it from getting entangled with unrelated app dependencies later.</p></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"permissions\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 06 / AUTHORIZATION</span>\n<h2>Permissions &amp; Groups \u2014 deciding what a known user can do</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Once identity is established (Sheet 01's distinction matters again here), the next question is what that identity is allowed to touch. Django's permission system is more granular than most newcomers expect.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>PERMISSIONS ARE JUST DATABASE ROWS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A \"permission\" in Django is, concretely, a row in a <code>Permission</code> table \u2014 identified by a string like <code>\"blog.add_post\"</code> or <code>\"blog.delete_post\"</code>. The moment you define a model, Django <strong>automatically creates four permissions for it</strong> (<code>add</code>, <code>change</code>, <code>delete</code>, <code>view</code>) during migration, with zero extra code. Checking a permission is just asking \"does this user have a relationship to this permission row?\" \u2014 either directly, or inherited through a group.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Groups \u2014 permission bundles, for sanity at scale</h3>\n<p>Assigning permissions to users one by one doesn't scale past a handful of accounts. A <strong>Group</strong> is just a named bundle of permissions \u2014 \"Editors,\" \"Moderators,\" \"Support Staff\" \u2014 and a user can belong to multiple groups, inheriting the union of all their permissions.</p>\n<figure class=\"diagram\">\n<svg aria-label=\"Diagram showing a user belonging to a group, which is connected to several permissions, illustrating inherited permission bundles\" role=\"img\" viewbox=\"0 0 600 200\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"300\" y=\"18\">PERMISSIONS VIA GROUP MEMBERSHIP</text>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"46\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\" width=\"120\" x=\"30\" y=\"80\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"90\" y=\"107\">User: maya</text>\n<path d=\"M150,103 L218,103\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#2f6b46\" height=\"46\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.4\" width=\"140\" x=\"220\" y=\"80\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"290\" y=\"107\">Group: Editors</text>\n<path d=\"M362,93 L450,55\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.2\"></path>\n<path d=\"M362,103 L450,103\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.2\"></path>\n<path d=\"M362,113 L450,151\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.2\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"32\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.2\" width=\"140\" x=\"452\" y=\"32\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"9.5\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"522\" y=\"53\">blog.add_post</text>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"32\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.2\" width=\"140\" x=\"452\" y=\"87\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"9.5\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"522\" y=\"108\">blog.change_post</text>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"32\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.2\" width=\"140\" x=\"452\" y=\"142\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"9.5\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"522\" y=\"163\">blog.view_post</text>\n</svg>\n<figcaption>maya gets all three permissions purely by being a member of the Editors group \u2014 no per-user assignment needed.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<h3>Checking permissions in code</h3>\n<pre><code><span># in a view</span>\n<span>if</span> request.user.has_perm(<span>\"blog.delete_post\"</span>):\n post.delete()\n\n<span># as a view decorator</span>\n<span>from</span> django.contrib.auth.decorators <span>import</span> permission_required\n\n<span>@permission_required</span>(<span>\"blog.delete_post\"</span>, raise_exception=<span>True</span>)\n<span>def</span> <span>delete_post</span>(request, pk):\n ...</code></pre>\n<pre><code><span>&lt;!-- in a template --&gt;</span>\n{% if perms.blog.delete_post %}\n &lt;button&gt;Delete&lt;/button&gt;\n{% endif %}</code></pre>\n<h3>Model-level vs. object-level permissions</h3>\n<p>Django's built-in system answers <em>\"can this user delete <strong>any</strong> Post?\"</em> \u2014 a model-level, blanket question. It does <strong>not</strong>, out of the box, answer <em>\"can this user delete <strong>this specific</strong> Post they don't own?\"</em> \u2014 that's object-level (a.k.a. row-level) permission checking, and it requires either custom logic in your view (<code>if post.author != request.user: raise PermissionDenied</code>) or a third-party package like <code>django-guardian</code> for a more general solution.</p>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>DON'T CONFUSE THE TWO LAYERS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>A genuinely common real-world bug: a view checks <code>has_perm(\"blog.change_post\")</code> (model-level \u2014 \"can edit posts in general\") and then happily lets that user edit <em>any</em> post by ID, including other people's. The permission check passed, but the authorization the developer actually intended \u2014 \"can edit <strong>their own</strong> post\" \u2014 was never written. Always ask which layer a check is actually operating at.</p></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"protecting-views\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 07 / GATEKEEPING</span>\n<h2>Protecting views \u2014 keeping anonymous visitors out</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Knowing how to check <code>request.user.is_authenticated</code> by hand in every view is correct but repetitive. Django gives you a decorator (for function-based views) and a mixin (for class-based views) so the check becomes a one-line declaration instead of a recurring <code>if</code> block.</p>\n<div class=\"grid2\">\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">FUNCTION-BASED VIEW</span>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib.auth.decorators <span>import</span> login_required\n\n<span>@login_required</span>\n<span>def</span> <span>dashboard</span>(request):\n <span>return</span> render(request, <span>\"dashboard.html\"</span>)</code></pre>\n</div>\n<div class=\"card\">\n<span class=\"eyebrow\">CLASS-BASED VIEW</span>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib.auth.mixins <span>import</span> LoginRequiredMixin\n\n<span>class</span> <span>Dashboard</span>(LoginRequiredMixin, TemplateView):\n template_name = <span>\"dashboard.html\"</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>WHAT ACTUALLY HAPPENS ON FAILURE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Both approaches do the same thing under the hood: check <code>request.user.is_authenticated</code> <em>before</em> your view body ever runs, and if it's <code>False</code>, redirect to <code>LOGIN_URL</code> with a <code>?next=/dashboard/</code> query parameter attached \u2014 so after a successful login, Django's built-in <code>LoginView</code> automatically bounces the user right back to the page they originally wanted. This is why <code>LOGIN_URL</code> (Sheet 04) needs to be set correctly \u2014 it's the single hinge this entire redirect dance depends on.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Stacking permission checks on top</h3>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib.auth.mixins <span>import</span> LoginRequiredMixin, PermissionRequiredMixin\n\n<span>class</span> <span>PostDelete</span>(LoginRequiredMixin, PermissionRequiredMixin, DeleteView):\n model = Post\n permission_required = <span>\"blog.delete_post\"</span>\n raise_exception = <span>True</span> <span># 403 instead of redirecting to login if logged-in-but-unauthorized</span></code></pre>\n<p>Notice the mixin order: <code>LoginRequiredMixin</code> comes first, so an anonymous user is redirected to log in (the friendlier outcome) rather than immediately hit with a blunt 403 they can't act on.</p>\n<h3>Protecting templates, not just views</h3>\n<p>A view-level check stops someone from reaching a page directly, but it's just as easy to forget that a shared template (like a navbar) might render a \"Delete\" link to users who'd be denied if they clicked it. Gate the link itself too:</p>\n<pre><code>{% if user.is_authenticated %}\n &lt;a href=<span>\"{% url 'logout' %}\"</span>&gt;Log out&lt;/a&gt;\n{% else %}\n &lt;a href=<span>\"{% url 'login' %}\"</span>&gt;Log in&lt;/a&gt;\n{% endif %}</code></pre>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>HIDING A LINK IS NOT THE SAME AS PROTECTING A VIEW</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>Hiding the \"Delete\" button in a template is a UX nicety, not a security boundary. Anyone can type a URL directly into their browser, bypassing your template entirely. <strong>Every</strong> view that performs a sensitive action must enforce its own check server-side \u2014 never rely on the frontend simply not showing the option.</p></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"auth-forms\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 08 / READY-MADE FORMS</span>\n<h2>The forms Django already wrote for you</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Just as <code>django.contrib.auth</code> ships views, it ships the forms that power them \u2014 already validating the fiddly rules you'd otherwise have to reimplement (password confirmation matching, password strength rules, \"this username is taken\").</p>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Form</th><th>Used for</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>UserCreationForm</code></td><td>Sign-up \u2014 username, password, password confirmation, with matching validation built in</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>AuthenticationForm</code></td><td>Login \u2014 what <code>LoginView</code> uses internally</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>PasswordChangeForm</code></td><td>Logged-in user changing their own password (requires old password)</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>PasswordResetForm</code></td><td>Step 1 of \"forgot password\" \u2014 collects an email, triggers the reset email</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SetPasswordForm</code></td><td>Step 2 of \"forgot password\" \u2014 sets a new password without needing the old one</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>UserChangeForm</code></td><td>Admin-style editing of an existing account</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3>Signup \u2014 the one screen Django doesn't fully provide</h3>\n<p>Interestingly, Django ships login, logout, and password-reset views, but <strong>not</strong> a ready-made signup view \u2014 account creation is considered too project-specific (what fields do you collect? is email verification required?) to standardize. <code>UserCreationForm</code> gives you most of the validation logic; you supply the view.</p>\n<pre><code><span># forms.py</span>\n<span>from</span> django.contrib.auth.forms <span>import</span> UserCreationForm\n<span>from</span> .models <span>import</span> User\n\n<span>class</span> <span>SignUpForm</span>(UserCreationForm):\n <span>class</span> <span>Meta</span>:\n model = User\n fields = [<span>\"username\"</span>, <span>\"email\"</span>] <span># password fields are added automatically</span>\n\n<span># views.py</span>\n<span>def</span> <span>signup</span>(request):\n <span>if</span> request.method == <span>\"POST\"</span>:\n form = SignUpForm(request.POST)\n <span>if</span> form.is_valid():\n user = form.save() <span># password is hashed automatically \u2014 never plaintext</span>\n login(request, user) <span># log them straight in after signup</span>\n <span>return</span> redirect(<span>\"dashboard\"</span>)\n <span>else</span>:\n form = SignUpForm()\n <span>return</span> render(request, <span>\"signup.html\"</span>, {<span>\"form\"</span>: form})</code></pre>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Mental Model</h4><span>WHY form.save() IS SAFE HERE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>Recall from the main Django Blueprint guide that a plain <code>ModelForm.save()</code> just writes field values straight to the database. <code>UserCreationForm</code> overrides this behavior specifically: its <code>save()</code> calls <code>user.set_password()</code> internally rather than writing the raw submitted password into the <code>password</code> field \u2014 this is the form quietly routing the value through Sheet 03's hashing machinery for you.</p></div>\n</div>\n<h3>Password validators \u2014 enforcing minimum strength</h3>\n<p>Beyond the form, Django runs a separate, configurable layer of <strong>password validators</strong> any time a password is set \u2014 independent checks for length, similarity to user attributes, common-password lists, and pure-numeric passwords.</p>\n<pre><code><span># settings.py</span>\nAUTH_PASSWORD_VALIDATORS = [\n {<span>\"NAME\"</span>: <span>\"django.contrib.auth.password_validation.UserAttributeSimilarityValidator\"</span>},\n {<span>\"NAME\"</span>: <span>\"django.contrib.auth.password_validation.MinimumLengthValidator\"</span>, <span>\"OPTIONS\"</span>: {<span>\"min_length\"</span>: 10}},\n {<span>\"NAME\"</span>: <span>\"django.contrib.auth.password_validation.CommonPasswordValidator\"</span>},\n {<span>\"NAME\"</span>: <span>\"django.contrib.auth.password_validation.NumericPasswordValidator\"</span>},\n]</code></pre>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"password-reset\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 09 / RECOVERY</span>\n<h2>The password reset flow, end to end</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">\"Forgot password\" is deceptively tricky to build correctly by hand \u2014 it has to prove someone controls an email address without ever requiring them to know their old password, while resisting being used to enumerate which emails have accounts. Django's built-in flow handles every step.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>THE TOKEN IS THE WHOLE TRICK</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>A password reset link looks like <code>/reset/MQ/abc123-xyz/</code>. That second segment is a cryptographically signed <strong>token</strong>, generated by Django's <code>PasswordResetTokenGenerator</code>. It encodes the user's ID and a timestamp, signed with your project's <code>SECRET_KEY</code> so it can't be forged \u2014 and critically, the token becomes invalid the moment the password actually changes (it's partly derived from the current password hash), so a reset link can't be reused twice or after the account's password has already been updated through it.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>The four-step dance</h3>\n<div class=\"flow-step\">\n<div class=\"fs-num\">1</div>\n<div class=\"fs-body\"><b>User submits their email</b> on a \"forgot password\" form (powered by <code>PasswordResetView</code> / <code>PasswordResetForm</code>).</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"flow-step\">\n<div class=\"fs-num\">2</div>\n<div class=\"fs-body\"><b>Django emails a unique, signed, time-limited link</b> containing the token \u2014 but only if that email actually matches an account, and even then, the on-screen confirmation message is identical either way (more on this below).</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"flow-step\">\n<div class=\"fs-num\">3</div>\n<div class=\"fs-body\"><b>User clicks the link</b>; <code>PasswordResetConfirmView</code> validates the token server-side and, if valid, shows a \"set new password\" form.</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"flow-step\">\n<div class=\"fs-num\">4</div>\n<div class=\"fs-body\"><b>New password is saved</b> (hashed, naturally) via <code>SetPasswordForm</code>, and the now-stale token can never be used again.</div>\n</div>\n<pre><code><span># urls.py</span>\n<span>from</span> django.contrib.auth <span>import</span> views <span>as</span> auth_views\n\nurlpatterns = [\n path(<span>\"reset/\"</span>, auth_views.PasswordResetView.as_view(), name=<span>\"password_reset\"</span>),\n path(<span>\"reset/done/\"</span>, auth_views.PasswordResetDoneView.as_view(), name=<span>\"password_reset_done\"</span>),\n path(<span>\"reset/&lt;uidb64&gt;/&lt;token&gt;/\"</span>, auth_views.PasswordResetConfirmView.as_view(), name=<span>\"password_reset_confirm\"</span>),\n path(<span>\"reset/complete/\"</span>, auth_views.PasswordResetCompleteView.as_view(), name=<span>\"password_reset_complete\"</span>),\n]</code></pre>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Critical Gotcha</h4><span>DON'T LEAK WHICH EMAILS EXIST</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>The \"Done\" confirmation page must say the same thing \u2014 something like \"If an account exists for that email, a reset link has been sent\" \u2014 <strong>whether or not that email actually matched a real account</strong>. Django's built-in view already does this correctly out of the box. If you ever customize this flow, resist the temptation to say \"no account found for that email\" \u2014 that single sentence turns your password reset form into a tool for discovering which emails are registered on your site.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>TOKEN LIFETIME</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<pre><code><span># settings.py \u2014 default is 3 days (259200 seconds)</span>\nPASSWORD_RESET_TIMEOUT = 3600 <span># tighten to 1 hour for a more security-conscious app</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>You still need a working email backend</h3>\n<p>None of this sends real email until you configure one. In development, Django's <code>console</code> backend just prints emails to your terminal \u2014 useful for testing the flow without a real mail server:</p>\n<pre><code><span># settings.py \u2014 development only</span>\nEMAIL_BACKEND = <span>\"django.core.mail.backends.console.EmailBackend\"</span>\n\n<span># settings.py \u2014 production, via a real transactional email provider</span>\nEMAIL_BACKEND = <span>\"django.core.mail.backends.smtp.EmailBackend\"</span>\nEMAIL_HOST = os.environ[<span>\"EMAIL_HOST\"</span>]\nEMAIL_HOST_USER = os.environ[<span>\"EMAIL_HOST_USER\"</span>]\nEMAIL_HOST_PASSWORD = os.environ[<span>\"EMAIL_HOST_PASSWORD\"</span>]\nEMAIL_USE_TLS = <span>True</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"signals\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 10 / REACTING TO IDENTITY EVENTS</span>\n<h2>Auth signals \u2014 reacting without coupling</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Beyond the model-save signals covered in the main Django Blueprint guide, <code>django.contrib.auth</code> broadcasts its own set of signals specifically for identity events \u2014 useful for audit logging, welcome emails, and security alerting, without tangling that logic into the login view itself.</p>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Signal</th><th>Fires when</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>user_logged_in</code></td><td>Immediately after a successful <code>login()</code> call</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>user_logged_out</code></td><td>Immediately after <code>logout()</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>user_login_failed</code></td><td>An <code>authenticate()</code> call fails \u2014 valuable for detecting brute-force attempts</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.contrib.auth.signals <span>import</span> user_logged_in, user_login_failed\n<span>from</span> django.dispatch <span>import</span> receiver\n\n<span>@receiver</span>(user_logged_in)\n<span>def</span> <span>log_successful_login</span>(sender, request, user, **kwargs):\n AuditLog.objects.create(user=user, event=<span>\"login_success\"</span>, ip=get_client_ip(request))\n\n<span>@receiver</span>(user_login_failed)\n<span>def</span> <span>log_failed_login</span>(sender, credentials, request, **kwargs):\n AuditLog.objects.create(event=<span>\"login_failed\"</span>, ip=get_client_ip(request))</code></pre>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Mental Model</h4><span>WHY USE A SIGNAL HERE INSTEAD OF JUST CODE IN THE VIEW</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>You <em>could</em> just write <code>AuditLog.objects.create(...)</code> directly inside your login view, right after calling <code>login()</code>. The advantage of the signal is that it fires no matter <em>which</em> code path triggers a login \u2014 your custom view, the built-in <code>LoginView</code>, the admin login, a management command, a third-party package's social-auth flow \u2014 all of them call the same underlying <code>login()</code> function, so a signal receiver registered once catches every single one, while view-level code only catches the specific views you remembered to edit.</p></div>\n</div>\n<h3>A common pattern: auto-creating a profile on signup</h3>\n<p>If you're extending behavior on user creation rather than changing the User model's own fields, a <code>post_save</code> signal on the User model itself is the standard hook for auto-creating a related object \u2014 a <code>Profile</code> row, a welcome notification, a default workspace:</p>\n<pre><code><span>from</span> django.db.models.signals <span>import</span> post_save\n<span>from</span> django.conf <span>import</span> settings\n\n<span>@receiver</span>(post_save, sender=settings.AUTH_USER_MODEL)\n<span>def</span> <span>create_profile</span>(sender, instance, created, **kwargs):\n <span>if</span> created:\n Profile.objects.create(user=instance)</code></pre>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>DON'T OVER-REACH WITH SIGNALS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>Signals are easy to overuse into a tangle of invisible side effects that make a codebase hard to trace \u2014 \"why did a welcome email just get sent? oh, there's a receiver in a completely unrelated app I forgot existed.\" For straightforward \"when X happens in this same flow, also do Y\" logic that lives conceptually in the same place, a direct function call in the view is usually more honest and far easier to debug than a signal.</p></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"sessions\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 11 / WHERE STATE ACTUALLY LIVES</span>\n<h2>Sessions, deeply \u2014 what's actually in that cookie?</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Sheet 01 promised that a session is \"just a database row and a cookie, pointing at each other.\" Time to make that literal.</p>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Concept \u2014 From Scratch</h4><span>THE COOKIE HOLDS NEXT TO NOTHING</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<p>Inspect your browser's cookies after logging into a Django site and you'll find one called <code>sessionid</code>, with a value like <code>8kj3n2pqz9x...</code> \u2014 an opaque random string. That's <strong>it</strong>. It is not your user ID, not your username, not anything meaningful on its own. It's a lookup key.</p>\n<p>On the server, Django maintains a session store \u2014 by default, a database table called <code>django_session</code> \u2014 with a row for every active session: the session key, an expiry date, and a blob of (signed) data, which for a logged-in user includes their user ID. Every request, Django takes the cookie's session key, looks up the matching row, reads the user ID out of the blob, and loads the corresponding <code>User</code> into <code>request.user</code>. <strong>The browser never holds your identity \u2014 only a claim ticket for it.</strong></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Session backends \u2014 where that row actually lives</h3>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Backend</th><th>Stores sessions in</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>db</code> (default)</td><td>The <code>django_session</code> database table</td><td>Simple, durable, the right default for most projects</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>cache</code></td><td>Your configured cache backend (e.g. Redis, Memcached)</td><td>Faster, but sessions vanish if the cache is flushed \u2014 only use with a persistent cache</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>cached_db</code></td><td>Both \u2014 cache for speed, database as the durable fallback</td><td>A common production sweet spot</td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>signed_cookies</code></td><td>The cookie itself, cryptographically signed \u2014 no server-side row at all</td><td>No database hit per request, but anyone who reads the cookie can see its contents (though not forge or alter it); avoid storing sensitive data in the session if using this backend</td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<pre><code><span># settings.py</span>\nSESSION_ENGINE = <span>\"django.contrib.sessions.backends.cached_db\"</span></code></pre>\n<h3>Expiry \u2014 how long a session stays valid</h3>\n<pre><code><span># settings.py</span>\nSESSION_COOKIE_AGE = 1209600 <span># seconds \u2014 default is 2 weeks</span>\nSESSION_EXPIRE_AT_BROWSER_CLOSE = <span>False</span> <span># True = session-only cookie, gone when browser closes</span>\nSESSION_SAVE_EVERY_REQUEST = <span>False</span> <span># True = sliding expiry, refreshed on every request</span></code></pre>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>LOGGING OUT EVERYWHERE</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>Because sessions are server-side rows, you can forcibly end a user's session from the server without their cooperation \u2014 useful for \"log out of all devices\" features or responding to a compromised account. Deleting their session row(s) from the <code>django_session</code> table (or calling <code>request.session.flush()</code> for the current session) instantly invalidates that cookie, anywhere it's used \u2014 this is the \"instant revocation\" advantage flagged back in Sheet 01's comparison table.</p></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Gotcha</h4><span>EXPIRED SESSIONS DON'T CLEAN THEMSELVES UP</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>With the database backend, expired session rows aren't automatically deleted \u2014 they just become unusable. Without periodic cleanup, the <code>django_session</code> table grows indefinitely. Run Django's built-in cleanup command on a schedule (a cron job, a Celery beat task):</p>\n<pre><code><span>python</span> manage.py clearsessions</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"hardening\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 12 / BEFORE GOING LIVE</span>\n<h2>Hardening auth for production</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Everything so far works correctly on <code>localhost</code>. A handful of settings exist specifically because the public internet is hostile in ways your dev machine never demonstrates.</p>\n<h3>Cookie security flags</h3>\n<table>\n<thead><tr><th>Setting</th><th>Does</th><th>Grade if missing</th></tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr><td><code>SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE</code></td><td>Cookie is only ever sent over HTTPS \u2014 never in plaintext over an unencrypted connection</td><td><span class=\"security-grade\">CRITICAL</span></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>CSRF_COOKIE_SECURE</code></td><td>Same protection for the CSRF cookie</td><td><span class=\"security-grade\">CRITICAL</span></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SESSION_COOKIE_HTTPONLY</code></td><td>JavaScript cannot read the cookie at all (default: <code>True</code>) \u2014 blunts cookie theft via XSS</td><td><span class=\"security-grade\">HIGH</span></td></tr>\n<tr><td><code>SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE</code></td><td>Restricts the cookie from being sent on cross-site requests \u2014 a core defense against CSRF</td><td><span class=\"security-grade\">HIGH</span></td></tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<pre><code><span># settings.py \u2014 production</span>\nSESSION_COOKIE_SECURE = <span>True</span>\nCSRF_COOKIE_SECURE = <span>True</span>\nSESSION_COOKIE_HTTPONLY = <span>True</span>\nSESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE = <span>\"Lax\"</span>\nSECURE_SSL_REDIRECT = <span>True</span>\nSECURE_HSTS_SECONDS = 31536000\nSECURE_HSTS_INCLUDE_SUBDOMAINS = <span>True</span></code></pre>\n<div class=\"box concept\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Mental Model</h4><span>WHY \"SECURE\" ISN'T THE DEFAULT</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p><code>SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE</code> defaults to <code>False</code> for a practical reason, not a security oversight: local development almost always runs over plain HTTP (<code>http://localhost:8000</code>), and a cookie marked \"Secure\" is refused entirely by the browser over HTTP \u2014 your dev login would silently break. This is exactly why split settings (covered in the main Blueprint guide) matter: dev and production genuinely need different values here, not just the same values \"to be safe.\"</p></div>\n</div>\n<h3>Rate limiting login attempts</h3>\n<p>Django's auth system has no built-in brute-force protection \u2014 nothing stops a script from attempting thousands of password guesses per minute against your login endpoint out of the box. This is commonly solved with a dedicated package rather than hand-rolled logic, since correct rate limiting (per-IP <em>and</em> per-account, with sane lockout/backoff behavior) is easy to get subtly wrong.</p>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>COMMON SOLUTIONS</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p><code>django-axes</code> locks out an account or IP after repeated failed attempts. <code>django-ratelimit</code> offers more general-purpose request throttling you can apply to any view, login included. Either is preferable to writing your own attempt-counter from scratch.</p></div>\n</div>\n<h3>Multi-factor authentication \u2014 mentioned, not detailed</h3>\n<p>Everything in this guide covers \"something you know\" (a password). Production systems protecting anything sensitive increasingly require a second factor \u2014 \"something you have\" (an authenticator app, an SMS code, a hardware key). Django doesn't ship MFA itself; <code>django-otp</code> and <code>django-two-factor-auth</code> are the established community packages that layer it on top of the session system covered here, without replacing any of it.</p>\n<h3>The pre-flight command</h3>\n<p>Before any of this matters in practice, run Django's own auditor \u2014 it specifically flags missing security settings against your live configuration:</p>\n<pre><code><span>python</span> manage.py check --deploy</code></pre>\n<h3>The full pre-launch checklist</h3>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n<li class=\"tone-success\">HTTPS enforced everywhere; HTTP requests redirect, never serve sensitive pages</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\"><code>SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE</code> and <code>CSRF_COOKIE_SECURE</code> both <code>True</code></li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">A custom user model decided <em>before</em> the first migration (Sheet 05) \u2014 can't retrofit easily</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Strong <code>AUTH_PASSWORD_VALIDATORS</code> configured, not left at bare minimums</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Generic error messages on login and password-reset \u2014 no account enumeration</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Rate limiting / lockout on the login endpoint via a dedicated package</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">A real, non-console <code>EMAIL_BACKEND</code> wired up for password resets</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\"><code>python manage.py clearsessions</code> scheduled on a recurring job</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\"><code>python manage.py check --deploy</code> run clean, with zero warnings</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"auth-flow\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 13 / SYNTHESIS</span>\n<h2>Tracing an authenticated request, start to finish</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">Every sheet above is one piece. Here's how they cooperate for a single concrete example: a logged-in user requesting a page protected by <code>@login_required</code>.</p>\n<figure class=\"diagram\">\n<svg aria-label=\"Step by step diagram tracing an authenticated request through cookie transmission, session lookup, AuthenticationMiddleware, login_required check, and the protected view\" role=\"img\" viewbox=\"0 0 700 480\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<text fill=\"#4a453c\" font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\" font-size=\"10\" letter-spacing=\"1.5\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"350\" y=\"20\">GET /dashboard/ \u2014 ALREADY LOGGED IN</text>\n<g font-family=\"JetBrains Mono\">\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"38\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"64\">1 \u00b7 Browser sends the request, sessionid cookie attached</text>\n<path d=\"M350,82 L350,98\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"98\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"124\">2 \u00b7 SessionMiddleware reads the cookie, loads the session row</text>\n<path d=\"M350,142 L350,158\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#2f6b46\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"158\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"184\">3 \u00b7 AuthenticationMiddleware sets request.user from the session</text>\n<path d=\"M350,202 L350,218\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#ffffff\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"218\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#1c1a16\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"244\">4 \u00b7 urls.py routes to the dashboard view</text>\n<path d=\"M350,262 L350,278\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#1c1a16\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#c8a15c\" stroke-width=\"1.4\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"278\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"304\">5 \u00b7 @login_required checks request.user.is_authenticated \u2192 True</text>\n<path d=\"M350,322 L350,338\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#2f6b46\" height=\"44\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"338\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" x=\"56\" y=\"364\">6 \u00b7 View body runs normally \u2014 request.user is the real account</text>\n<path d=\"M350,382 L350,398\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" stroke=\"#1c1a16\" stroke-width=\"1.3\"></path>\n<rect fill=\"#1c1a16\" height=\"40\" stroke=\"#c8a15c\" stroke-width=\"1.6\" width=\"620\" x=\"40\" y=\"398\"></rect>\n<text fill=\"#ffffff\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" x=\"350\" y=\"423\">7 \u00b7 Rendered page returns to the browser</text>\n</g>\n</svg>\n<figcaption>If the cookie were missing or the session expired, step 5 would redirect to LOGIN_URL instead of reaching step 6.</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<div class=\"pillquote\">\"Every protected page you'll ever build is some variation of this same seven-step shape.\"</div>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section id=\"auth-tips\">\n\n<div>\n<span>SHEET 14 / FIELD NOTES</span>\n<h2>Pro tips, conventions, and traps to avoid</h2>\n<p class=\"lede\">A consolidated punch list specific to authentication \u2014 the kind of thing that takes a security incident to learn the hard way otherwise.</p>\n<h3>Identity correctness</h3>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Decide on a custom user model before your first <code>migrate</code> \u2014 there is no comfortable way to add this later.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Always check <code>request.user.is_authenticated</code>, never truthiness of <code>request.user</code> \u2014 it's never <code>None</code>.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Never confuse model-level permission checks with object-level ownership checks \u2014 they answer different questions.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Treat <code>is_active</code>, <code>is_staff</code>, and <code>is_superuser</code> as three independent switches, not a hierarchy.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Password &amp; credential hygiene</h3>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Never write custom password-hashing code \u2014 always <code>set_password()</code> / Django's hashers.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Use identical, generic error messages on login failure and password-reset request, regardless of which part actually failed.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Set meaningful <code>AUTH_PASSWORD_VALIDATORS</code> \u2014 the framework defaults are a reasonable floor, not a ceiling.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Consider Argon2 over the PBKDF2 default for new projects with stronger threat models.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Session &amp; cookie discipline</h3>\n<ul class=\"checklist\">\n<li class=\"tone-success\"><code>SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE</code> and <code>CSRF_COOKIE_SECURE</code> must be <code>True</code> in production \u2014 never ship with dev defaults.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Schedule <code>clearsessions</code> \u2014 expired rows don't clean themselves up.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Use <code>request.session.flush()</code> (or delete the row directly) for genuine \"log out everywhere\" / compromised-account response.</li>\n<li class=\"tone-success\">Don't store large or sensitive blobs in the session if you're on the <code>signed_cookies</code> backend \u2014 the data sits client-side, just signed, not encrypted.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"box tone-tip\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Tip</h4><span>THE SHELL, AGAIN, FOR AUTH SPECIFICALLY</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\">\n<pre><code><span>python</span> manage.py shell\n&gt;&gt;&gt; <span>from</span> django.contrib.auth <span>import</span> get_user_model\n&gt;&gt;&gt; User = get_user_model()\n&gt;&gt;&gt; u = User.objects.get(username=<span>\"maya\"</span>)\n&gt;&gt;&gt; u.check_password(<span>\"a guess\"</span>) <span># sanity-check hashing/auth logic live, no view needed</span></code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"box tone-danger\">\n<div class=\"box-head\"><h4>Last Word</h4><span>SECURITY IS A PROCESS, NOT A SETTING</span></div>\n<div class=\"box-body\"><p>Every setting in this guide is necessary but none is sufficient on its own. A project with perfect cookie flags and a weak rate-limiting story is still vulnerable; a project with airtight password hashing but leaked error messages still leaks account existence. Treat Sheet 12's checklist as a floor to clear before launch, then keep revisiting it as the project and its threat model grow.</p></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</section>";

